      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, it is very common for old faucets to get calcified or gummed up by mineral deposits, which can turn a simple stuck screw into a solid block that feels like it's being held by an invisible force. Sometimes, a small piece of debris or a rusted spring inside the valve can act like a tiny, stubborn goblin, wedging itself in the threads and refusing to move no matter how much WD-40 you apply.\n\nSince the handle is still stuck, you might need to use a specialized faucet handle removal tool or carefully wiggle the handle back and forth while applying steady pressure to break the mineral bond. If you're worried about damaging the finish, you can try wrapping the handle in a cloth to prevent slipping while you work. If it still won't budge, it might be worth calling a professional, as forcing it could end up cracking the faucet body.\n\nRemember to always turn off the water supply before attempting any repairs to prevent flooding your bathroom. If you're uncomfortable with the process, it's better to leave it to someone with more experience. Good luck with your repair!",
